  <h1>Common ADA Claim Misconceptions</h1>
  <p><em>Reviewed by Riley Chen (RC), Employment &amp; Civil Rights Practice Lead. Updated May 2026.</em></p>
  <h2>&ldquo;I have to be completely disabled to have an ADA claim.&rdquo;</h2>
  <p>False. The ADA covers any physical or mental impairment that substantially limits a major life activity. After the 2008 amendments, this is interpreted broadly. Part-time impairments, episodic conditions, and conditions in remission can qualify. You don&rsquo;t need to be unable to work.</p>
  <h2>&ldquo;My employer has to give me whatever accommodation I ask for.&rdquo;</h2>
  <p>Not quite. The employer must provide an <em>effective</em> accommodation &mdash; not necessarily the specific one you requested. If your preferred accommodation would cause undue hardship, the employer can offer an alternative that also allows you to perform the essential functions.</p>
  <h2>&ldquo;The EEOC will fight my case for me.&rdquo;</h2>
  <p>The EEOC investigates and sometimes litigates, but it cannot litigate every case. In most cases, the EEOC issues a right-to-sue letter and the individual must pursue the claim privately. The EEOC process is a required procedural step, not a guarantee of enforcement.</p>
  <h2>&ldquo;I can sue immediately without going to the EEOC.&rdquo;</h2>
  <p>False for Title I employment claims. You must exhaust administrative remedies by filing with the EEOC first. Skipping this step means any subsequent lawsuit will be dismissed.</p>
  <h2>&ldquo;There is no cap on ADA damages.&rdquo;</h2>
  <p>Compensatory and punitive damages are capped by employer size (ranging from $50K to $300K). However, back pay, front pay, and attorney fees are not subject to the cap &mdash; and in many cases they dwarf the capped damages.</p>
  <h2>&ldquo;Temporary conditions don&rsquo;t count.&rdquo;</h2>
  <p>Post-2008, even temporary conditions can qualify if they substantially limit a major life activity during the period of impairment. A broken leg requiring 3 months of accommodation may be protected.</p>
  <h2>Where to go from here</h2>
